#!/usr/bin/env ruby

# Points you at the right deployment guide for where this app is going.
# The app itself is deployment-agnostic — the full portable contract lives
# in the "Deploying without Kamal" section of app/docs/developer/deployment.md
# (rendered at /docs/developer/deployment in the running app).

TARGETS = {
  "kamal" => "A VPS or cloud server you manage, deployed with Kamal (the template default)",
  "self-host" => "Hardware you own (Mac, home server) running the Kamal stack",
  "managed" => "A managed platform (Hatchbox or similar) — no infrastructure to run"
}.freeze

GUIDES = {
  "kamal" => <<~TEXT,
    Deploying with Kamal (template default)
    =======================================

    1. Read /docs/developer/deployment in the running app (source: app/docs/developer/deployment.md).
       It covers first deploy, the SQLite single-host invariants, Solid Queue
       topology, and SSL.
    2. config/deploy.yml IS the configuration reference — every option is
       documented inline. Set service/image/volume names (see /docs/developer/forking),
       your server's IP or hostname, and proxy.host.
    3. Generate production credentials (bin/rails credentials:edit --environment
       production); .kamal/secrets reads config/credentials/production.key.
    4. First deploy: bin/kamal setup. After that: bin/kamal deploy.

    Keep max-replicas: 1 and SOLID_QUEUE_IN_PUMA: true until you graduate off
    SQLite — the deploy.yml comments explain the checklist.
  TEXT
  "self-host" => <<~TEXT,
    Self-hosting on your own hardware
    =================================

    Everything from `bin/deploy-guide kamal` applies — the app doesn't care
    whose metal it runs on. Your hardware additionally needs:

    - A Docker engine Kamal can drive: `ssh you@host 'docker version'` must work
      non-interactively. On macOS hosts that means a headless engine (Colima)
      and a PATH visible to non-interactive shells.
    - Ports 80 and 443 publicly reachable (router port-forward + static IP or
      DDNS) so kamal-proxy can obtain Let's Encrypt certificates via HTTP-01.
    - DNS: a wildcard record (*.apps.example.com) makes every future app on the
      box zero-DNS-work.
    - Unattended operation: auto-restart after power failure, no sleep, and the
      Docker engine starting at boot — test by pulling the plug once.

    Then follow /docs/developer/deployment (app/docs/developer/deployment.md) as for any Kamal
    target.
  TEXT
  "managed" => <<~TEXT
    Deploying to a managed platform (Hatchbox or similar)
    =====================================================

    You can ignore config/deploy.yml, .kamal/, and bin/kamal entirely — leave
    them in place so upstream template merges stay clean. Nothing in app code
    reads them. Your platform needs to provide:

    Required
    --------
    - RAILS_MASTER_KEY  env var: contents of config/credentials/production.key
    - A persistent, writable storage/ directory (SQLite databases + Active
      Storage files must survive deploys)
    - Health check endpoint: /up
    - SOLID_QUEUE_IN_PUMA=true — without it NO background jobs run (so no
      emails). Alternative: run bin/jobs as a separate worker process instead.
    - RAILS_HOST: your app's hostname (mailer links; defaults to example.com!)

    Optional tuning (working defaults)
    ----------------------------------
    - WEB_CONCURRENCY (1), RAILS_MAX_THREADS (3), JOB_CONCURRENCY (1),
      RAILS_LOG_LEVEL (info)
    - Preset/seed variables (SIGNUP_MODE, TENANCY_*, ...): see /docs/developer/presets
      and .env.example

    The one constraint that follows you everywhere
    ----------------------------------------------
    SQLite is single-writer: run exactly one web instance. Scaling to a second
    server/dyno is the same corruption risk as max-replicas: 2 under Kamal.
    Graduate to Postgres first (see /docs/developer/deployment).

    Full contract: "Deploying without Kamal" in /docs/developer/deployment
    (source: app/docs/developer/deployment.md).
  TEXT
}.freeze

def usage(io = $stdout)
  io.puts "Usage: bin/deploy-guide [TARGET]"
  io.puts
  io.puts "Where are you deploying? Pick a target:"
  io.puts
  TARGETS.each { |name, description| io.puts format("  %-10s %s", name, description) }
  io.puts
  io.puts "Run bin/deploy-guide TARGET for the guide."
end

target = ARGV.first

case target
when nil
  usage
  if $stdin.tty?
    print "\n> "
    choice = $stdin.gets&.strip
    if choice && GUIDES.key?(choice)
      puts
      puts GUIDES[choice]
    end
  end
when "-h", "--help"
  usage
when *TARGETS.keys
  puts GUIDES[target]
else
  warn "Unknown target: #{target.inspect}"
  usage($stderr)
  exit 1
end
